result.execSummary:
The defendant Jordan M. Funmaker was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Criminal Trespass to Dwelling [Modifiers: Domestic Abuse], a class A misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 943.14(2).
  • Criminal Damage to Property, a class A misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 943.01(1).
  • Battery, a class A misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 940.19(1).

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

3:40 PM Defendant Jordan M. Funmaker in court.  Attorney Joseph J. Kaupie in court for Jordan M. Funmaker.  Attorney Crystal Leigh Jensen in court for State of Wisconsin. 22CF30 case brought in for sentencing purposes. State is satisfied they are incompliance with victim rights. Defendant in agreement to resolving all cases today, and ok with Judge Becker dealing w/Judge Diehn's case 22CF30. 
21CF174 single count - def enters a plea of Guilty. 22CF84 - Count 3, Defendant enters a plea of Guilty, Count 4, pleads Guilty, Count 5, pleads guilty. All other charges as well as 21CM127 and 22CF30 DRI. 
Court reviewed the elements and potential penalties of the charge the defendant plead to.  He understood.   Court reviewed the plea questionnaire, constitutional rights and elements with the defendant. Felony warnings given.  He understood. Defense stipulated that there is a factual basis for the plea.   Court found that the defendant freely, voluntarily, knowingly and intelligently entered his plea and waived his constitutional rights.  Court found that a factual basis exists for the plea.  Found guilty of 21CF174 Ct 1 -Battery or Threat to Judge, Prosecutor, or Law Enforcement Officer contrary to 940.203(2), 22CF84 - Ct 2?  should be Ct 3, Criminal Trespass to Dwelling contrary to 943.12(2) -  Ct 4 - Criminal Damage to Property contrary to 943.01(1),  Ct 5 - Battery contrary to 940.19(1).  Defendant did not exercise his right to allocution. 

Joint recommendation: Withhold sentence, 3 yrs probation, risk and needs assessment and follow through with agents recommendations, AODA, in addition to 21CF174 - no contact w/victim unless in his own official capacity or victims family. 22CF84 - no contact with T.P. and C.B. per her and the agents consent. 16 days credit on 21CF174. 

Court adopts joint recommendation: Withhold sentence, orders 3 yrs probation, risk and needs assessment and follow through with and comply with  agents recommendations, AODA. In addition to 21CF174 - no contact w/victim unless in his own official capacity or victims family. 22CF84 - no contact with T.P. or C.B., other than for C.B. in the context of dealing with any child rearing emergencies or essential information to communicate for the betterment of the children and that the parties would be making any physical changes of their children through a third party unless C.B. and your probation agent agree otherwise. 
16 days jail credit, if revoked on 21CF174. Pay Court costs through probation.  Court advised defendant of the DNA submission requirement. Ordered to report to JC probation by noon tomorrow.
